# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: attention-variants
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] In machine learning, **attention** is a method that determines the importance of each component in a sequence relative to the other components in that sequence.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] In natural language processing, importance is represented by "soft" weights assigned to each word in a sentence.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] More generally, attention encodes vectors called token embeddings across a fixed-width sequence that can range from tens to millions of tokens in size.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Unlike "hard" weights, which are computed during the backwards training pass, "soft" weights exist only in the forward pass and therefore change with every step of the input.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Earlier designs implemented the attention mechanism in a serial recurrent neural network (RNN) language translation system, but a more recent design, namely the transformer, removed the slower sequential RNN and relied more heavily on the faster parallel attention scheme.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Inspired by ideas about attention in humans, the attention mechanism was developed to address the weaknesses of using information from the hidden layers of recurrent neural networks.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Recurrent neural networks favor information contained in words at the end of a sentence and thus deemed more recent, thereby tending to attenuate the significance and associated predictive weight assigned to information earlier in the sentence.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Attention allows a token equal access to any part of a sentence directly, rather than only through the previous state.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Additional surveys of the attention mechanism in deep learning are provided by Niu et al. and Soydaner.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] The major breakthrough came with self-attention, where each element in the input sequence attends to all others, enabling the model to capture global dependencies.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] This idea was central to the Transformer architecture, which replaced recurrence with attention mechanisms.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] As a result, Transformers became the foundation for models like BERT, T5 and generative pre-trained transformers (GPT).
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] The modern era of machine attention was revitalized by grafting an attention mechanism (Fig 1. orange) to an Encoder-Decoder.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Figure 2 shows the internal step-by-step operation of the attention block (A) in Fig 1.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] The diagram shows the attention forward pass calculating correlations of the word "that" with other words in "See that girl run." Given the right weights from training, the network should be able to identify "girl" as a highly correlated word.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] In translating between languages, alignment is the process of matching words from the source sentence to words of the translated sentence.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Networks that perform verbatim translation without regard to word order would show the highest scores along the (dominant) diagonal of the matrix.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] The off-diagonal dominance shows that the attention mechanism is more nuanced.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Consider an example of translating *I love you* to French.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] On the first pass through the decoder, 94% of the attention weight is on the first English word *I*, so the network offers the word *je*.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] On the second pass of the decoder, 88% of the attention weight is on the third English word *you*, so it offers *t'*.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] On the last pass, 95% of the attention weight is on the second English word *love*, so it offers *aime*.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] In the *I love you* example, the second word *love* is aligned with the third word *aime*.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Sometimes, alignment can be multiple-to-multiple.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] For example, the English phrase *look it up* corresponds to *cherchez-le*.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] For convolutional neural networks, attention mechanisms can be distinguished by the dimension on which they operate, namely: spatial attention, channel attention, or combinations.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] These variants recombine the encoder-side inputs to redistribute those effects to each target output.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Often, a correlation-style matrix of dot products provides the re-weighting coefficients.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] In the figures below, W is the matrix of context attention weights, similar to the formula in Overview section above.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] The size of the attention matrix is proportional to the square of the number of input tokens.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Therefore, when the input is long, calculating the attention matrix requires a lot of GPU memory.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Flash attention is an implementation that reduces the memory needs and increases efficiency without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] It achieves this by partitioning the attention computation into smaller blocks that fit into the GPU's faster on-chip memory, reducing the need to store large intermediate matrices and thus lowering memory usage while increasing computational efficiency.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] FlexAttention is an attention kernel developed by Meta that allows users to modify attention scores prior to softmax and dynamically chooses the optimal attention algorithm.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Attention is widely used in natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] In NLP, it improves context understanding in tasks like question answering and summarization.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] In vision, visual attention helps models focus on relevant image regions, enhancing object detection and image captioning.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] From the original paper on vision transformers (ViT), visualizing attention scores as a heat map (called saliency maps or attention maps) has become an important and routine way to inspect the decision making process of ViT models.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] One can compute the attention maps with respect to any attention head at any layer, while the deeper layers tend to show more semantically meaningful visualization.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Attention rollout is a recursive algorithm to combine attention scores across all layers, by computing the dot product of successive attention maps.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Because vision transformers are typically trained in a self-supervised manner, attention maps are generally not class-sensitive.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] When a classification head is attached to the ViT backbone, class-discriminative attention maps (CDAM) combines attention maps and gradients with respect to the class `[CLS]` token.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Some class-sensitive interpretability methods originally developed for convolutional neural networks can be also applied to ViT, such as GradCAM, which back-propagates the gradients to the outputs of the final attention layer.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Using attention as basis of explanation for the transformers in language and vision is not without debate.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] While some pioneering papers analyzed and framed attention scores as explanations, higher attention scores do not always correlate with greater impact on model performances.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] The matrix Q contains m queries, while matrices $K,V$ jointly contain an *unordered* set of n key-value pairs.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Value vectors in matrix V are weighted using the weights resulting from the softmax operation, so that the rows of the m -by- $d_{v}$ output matrix are confined to the convex hull of the points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d_{v}}$ given by the rows of V .
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] To understand the permutation invariance and permutation equivariance properties of QKV attention, let $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}$ and $B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ be permutation matrices; and $D\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ an arbitrary matrix.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] These properties are inherited when applying linear transforms to the inputs and outputs of QKV attention blocks.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] For example, a simple self-attention function defined as: $X\mapsto {\text{Attention}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is permutation equivariant with respect to re-ordering the rows of the input matrix X in a non-trivial way, because every row of the output is a function of all the rows of the input.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Similar properties hold for *multi-head attention*, which is defined below.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] The softmax output, also in $\mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is then *lower triangular*, with zeros in all elements above the diagonal.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] The masking ensures that for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ , row i of the attention output is independent of row j of any of the three input matrices.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] The permutation invariance and equivariance properties of standard QKV attention do not hold for the masked variant.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] The permutation properties of (standard, unmasked) QKV attention apply here also.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] For permutation matrices, $A,B$ : ${\text{MultiHead}}(AQ,BK,BV)=A\,{\text{MultiHead}}(Q,K,V)$ from which we also see that multi-head self-attention: $X\mapsto {\text{MultiHead}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is equivariant with respect to re-ordering of the rows of input matrix X .
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] ${\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}(QWK^{T})V$ where W is a learnable weight matrix.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Self-attention is essentially the same as cross-attention, except that query, key, and value vectors all come from the same model.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] Both encoder and decoder can use self-attention, but with subtle differences.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] For encoder self-attention, we can start with a simple encoder without self-attention, such as an "embedding layer", which simply converts each input word into a vector by a fixed lookup table.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] This gives a sequence of hidden vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ .
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] This can be applied repeatedly, to obtain a multilayered encoder.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] This is the "encoder self-attention", sometimes called the "all-to-all attention", as the vector at every position can attend to every other.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] For decoder self-attention, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because during the autoregressive decoding process, the decoder cannot attend to future outputs that has yet to be decoded.
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] This can be solved by forcing the attention weights $w_{ij}=0$ for all $i<j$ , called "causal masking".
[src:attention-variants/attention-machine-learning] This attention mechanism is the "causally masked self-attention".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:attention-variants/flashattention-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The **softmax function,** also known as **softargmax** or **normalized exponential function**, converts a tuple of K real numbers into a probability distribution over K possible outcomes.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] It is a generalization of the logistic function to multiple dimensions, and is used in multinomial logistic regression.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The softmax function is often used as the last activation function of a neural network to normalize the output of a network to a probability distribution over predicted output classes.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The softmax function takes as input a tuple z of K real numbers, and normalizes it into a probability distribution consisting of K probabilities proportional to the exponentials of the input numbers.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] That is, prior to applying softmax, some tuple components could be negative, or greater than one; and might not sum to 1; but after applying softmax, each component will be in the interval $(0,1)$ , and the components will add up to 1, so that they can be interpreted as probabilities.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Furthermore, the larger input components will correspond to larger probabilities.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] In words, the softmax applies the standard exponential function to each element $z_{i}$ of the input tuple $\mathbf {z}$ (consisting of K real numbers), and normalizes these values by dividing by the sum of all these exponentials.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The normalization ensures that the sum of the components of the output vector $\sigma (\mathbf {z} )$ is 1.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The term "softmax" derives from the amplifying effects of the exponential on any maxima in the input tuple.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] For example, the standard softmax of $(1,2,8)$ is approximately $(0.001,0.002,0.997)$ , which amounts to assigning almost all of the total unit weight in the result to the position of the tuple's maximal element (of 8).
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] In general, instead of e a different base b > 0 can be used.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] As above, if b > 1 then larger input components will result in larger output probabilities, and increasing the value of b will create probability distributions that are more concentrated around the positions of the largest input values.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Conversely, if 0 < b < 1 then smaller input components will result in larger output probabilities, and decreasing the value of b will create probability distributions that are more concentrated around the positions of the smallest input values.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] A value proportional to the reciprocal of β is sometimes referred to as the *temperature*: ${\textstyle \beta =1/kT}$ , where k is typically 1 or the Boltzmann constant and T is the temperature.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] A higher temperature results in a more uniform output distribution (i.e. with higher entropy; it is "more random"), while a lower temperature results in a sharper output distribution, with one value dominating.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] In some fields, the base is fixed, corresponding to a fixed scale, while in others the parameter β (or T) is varied.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The softmax function is a multiple-variable generalization of the logistic function.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The Softmax function is a smooth approximation to the arg max function: the function whose value is the *index* of a tuple's largest element.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Softmax is not a smooth maximum (that is, a smooth approximation to the maximum function).
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The term "softmax" is also used for the closely related LogSumExp function, which is a smooth maximum.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] For this reason, some prefer the more accurate term "softargmax", though the term "softmax" is conventional in machine learning.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] This section uses the term "softargmax" for clarity.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] For example, in this encoding $\operatorname {arg\,max} (1,5,10)=(0,0,1),$ since the third argument is the maximum.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] This can be generalized to multiple arg max values (multiple equal $z_{i}$ being the maximum) by dividing the 1 between all max args; formally 1/k where k is the number of arguments assuming the maximum.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] With the last expression given in the introduction, softargmax is now a smooth approximation of arg max: as ⁠ $\beta \to \infty$ ⁠, softargmax converges to arg max.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] In fact, softargmax is continuous, but arg max is not continuous at the singular set where two coordinates are equal, while the uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The reason it fails to converge uniformly is that for inputs where two coordinates are almost equal (and one is the maximum), the arg max is the index of one or the other, so a small change in input yields a large change in output.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] However, softargmax does converge compactly on the non-singular set.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Conversely, as ⁠ $\beta \to -\infty$ ⁠, softargmax converges to arg min in the same way, where here the singular set is points with two arg *min* values.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] It is also the case that, for any fixed β, if one input ⁠ $z_{i}$ ⁠ is much larger than the others *relative* to the temperature, $T=1/\beta$ , the output is approximately the arg max.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The softmax function is used in various multiclass classification methods, such as multinomial logistic regression (also known as softmax regression), multiclass linear discriminant analysis, naive Bayes classifiers, and artificial neural networks.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The operation is equivalent to applying a linear operator defined by $\mathbf {w}$ to tuples $\mathbf {x}$ , thus transforming the original, probably highly-dimensional, input to vectors in a K-dimensional space $\mathbb {R} ^{K}$ .
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The standard softmax function is often used in the final layer of a neural network-based classifier.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Such networks are commonly trained under a log loss (or cross-entropy) regime, giving a non-linear variant of multinomial logistic regression.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Here, the Kronecker delta is used for simplicity (cf. the derivative of a sigmoid function, being expressed via the function itself).
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] To ensure stable numerical computations subtracting the maximum value from the input tuple is common.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] This approach, while not altering the output or the derivative theoretically, enhances stability by directly controlling the maximum exponent value computed.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] If the function is scaled with the parameter $\beta$ , then these expressions must be multiplied by $\beta$ .
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] See multinomial logit for a probability model which uses the softmax activation function.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] In the field of reinforcement learning, a softmax function can be used to convert values into action probabilities.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] where the action value $q_{t}(a)$ corresponds to the expected reward of following action a and $\tau$ is called a temperature parameter (in allusion to statistical mechanics).
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] For high temperatures ( $\tau \to \infty$ ), all actions have nearly the same probability and the lower the temperature, the more expected rewards affect the probability.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] For a low temperature ( $\tau \to 0^{+}$ ), the probability of the action with the highest expected reward tends to 1.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] In neural network applications, the number K of possible outcomes is often large, e.g. in case of neural language models that predict the most likely outcome out of a vocabulary which might contain millions of possible words.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] This can make the calculations for the softmax layer (i.e. the matrix multiplications to determine the $z_{i}$ , followed by the application of the softmax function itself) computationally expensive.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] What's more, the gradient descent backpropagation method for training such a neural network involves calculating the softmax for every training example, and the number of training examples can also become large.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The computational effort for the softmax became a major limiting factor in the development of larger neural language models, motivating various remedies to reduce training times.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Approaches that reorganize the softmax layer for more efficient calculation include the **hierarchical softmax** and the **differentiated softmax**.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The hierarchical softmax (introduced by Morin and Bengio in 2005) uses a binary tree structure where the outcomes (vocabulary words) are the leaves and the intermediate nodes are suitably selected "classes" of outcomes, forming latent variables.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The desired probability (softmax value) of a leaf (outcome) can then be calculated as the product of the probabilities of all nodes on the path from the root to that leaf.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Ideally, when the tree is balanced, this would reduce the computational complexity from $O(K)$ to $O(\log _{2}K)$ .
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] In practice, results depend on choosing a good strategy for clustering the outcomes into classes.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] A Huffman tree was used for this in Google's word2vec models (introduced in 2013) to achieve scalability.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] A second kind of remedies is based on approximating the softmax (during training) with modified loss functions that avoid the calculation of the full normalization factor.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] These include methods that restrict the normalization sum to a sample of outcomes (e.g.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The standard softmax is numerically unstable because of large exponentiations.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Subtracting by it guarantees that the exponentiations result in at most 1, see translation invariance in the mathematical properties.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] It can be efficiently computed on a GPU cluster using the FlashAttention algorithm.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Along the main diagonal $(x,\,x,\,\dots ,\,x),$ softmax is just the uniform distribution on outputs, $(1/n,\dots ,1/n)$ : equal scores yield equal probabilities.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Geometrically, softmax is constant along diagonals: this is the dimension that is eliminated, and corresponds to the softmax output being independent of a translation in the input scores (a choice of 0 score).
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] By contrast, softmax is not invariant under scaling.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The standard logistic function is the special case for a 1-dimensional axis in 2-dimensional space, say the *x*-axis in the (x, y) plane.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The softmax function was used in statistical mechanics as the Boltzmann distribution in the foundational paper Boltzmann (1868), formalized and popularized in the influential textbook Gibbs (1902).
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The use of the softmax in decision theory is credited to R.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Duncan Luce, who used the axiom of independence of irrelevant alternatives in rational choice theory to deduce the softmax in Luce's choice axiom for relative preferences.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] In machine learning, the term "softmax" is credited to John S.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The output has most of its weight where the "4" was in the original input.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] This is what the function is normally used for: to highlight the largest values and suppress values which are significantly below the maximum value.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] But note: a change of *temperature* changes the output.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] This shows that high temperatures de-emphasize the maximum value.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] The softmax function generates probability predictions densely distributed over its support.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Other functions like sparsemax or α-entmax can be used when sparse probability predictions are desired.
[src:attention-variants/softmax-function] Also the Gumbel-softmax reparametrization trick can be used when sampling from a discrete-discrete distribution needs to be mimicked in a differentiable manner.
